\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Bertrand Duopoly}
\begin{itemize}
    \item The Cournot model assumed that the firms choose quantities and the market price comes from consumer demand. 
    \item Bertrand (1883) argue that firms often set prices and consumers choose from where they will purchase based on prices. 
    \item Firms produce identical goods, and each firm posts a price. 
    \item Consumers buy from the firm that offers lowest price.
    
\end{itemize}
    \end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Bertrand Duopoly}
Assume that the inverse demand is given by $p=100-q$, and cost functions are $c_i(q_i)=cq_i$. Consumers buy from the firm whose price is the lowest. In case of a tie, market splits equally between two firms. 
\par 
The normal-form representation of the game:
 \begin{enumerate}
        \item \textbf{Players:} $N=\{1,2\}$.
        \item \textbf{Actions:} $S_1=S_2=[0,\infty)$, and firms choose prices $p_1$, $p_2$.
        \item Given our assumption, the quantities are given: 
        $$q_1(p_1,p_2)=\begin{cases} 100-p_1, & \text{ if } p_1<p_2,  \\
        0 , & \text{ if }p_1>p_2, \\
        \frac{100-p_1}{2}, & \text{ if } p_1=p_2.
        \end{cases}$$
         $$q_2(p_1,p_2)=\begin{cases} 100-p_2, & \text{ if } p_2<p_1,  \\
        0 , & \text{ if }p_2>p_1, \\
        \frac{100-p_2}{2}, & \text{ if } p_1=p_2.
        \end{cases}$$
    \end{enumerate}

\end{frame}


\begin{frame}{Bertrand Duopoly}

 \begin{enumerate}
       \item Therefore, the profit of each firm will be
        $$\pi_1(p_1,p_2)=\begin{cases} (100-p_1)(p_1-c), & \text{ if } p_1<p_2,  \\
        0 , & \text{ if }p_1>p_2, \\
        \frac{100-p_1}{2}(p_1-c), & \text{ if } p_1=p_2.
        \end{cases}$$
         $$\pi_2(p_1,p_2)=\begin{cases} (100-p_2)(p_2-c), & \text{ if } p_2<p_1,  \\
        0 , & \text{ if }p_2>p_1, \\
        \frac{100-p_2}{2}(p_2-c), & \text{ if } p_1=p_2.
        \end{cases}$$
    \end{enumerate}

\end{frame}
\begin{frame}{Bertrand Duopoly}
    \begin{block}{Proposition}
    There is a unique Nash equilibrium in this game: $p_1=p_2=c$.
    \end{block}
    \textbf{Proof:} First note that in any equilibrium $p_i\geq c$ for both firms - otherwise firm offering a price lower than c will lose money. We need to show that $p_i>c$ cannot be part of any equilibrium. We can see this in two steps:
    \begin{enumerate}
        \item If $p_1=p_2=\hat p>c$ then each would benefit from lowering its price to some price $\hat p-\varepsilon$ ($\varepsilon$ very small) and get the whole market for almost the same price.
        \item If $p_1> p_2 \geq c$ then player 2 would want to deviate to $p_1-\varepsilon$ ($\varepsilon$ very small) and earn higher profits. 
    \end{enumerate}
    
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Bertrand Duopoly}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item It's intuitive why $p_1=p_2=c$ is an equilibrium: Firm $i$'s best response to $p_j=c$ is $p_i(c)\geq c$. 
        \item Any price at or above marginal costs c is a best response to the other player charging c.
        \item Hence, $p_1=p_2=c$ is the equilibrium because each is playing a best response to the other's choice and neither wants to deviate to a different price. 
    \end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Bertrand Duopoly}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Remember that competitive price was $p^{CE}=c$. 
        \item We showed that when firms are competing in prices, then market behaves like in case of perfect competition, prices being $p_1=p_2=c$. 
        \item Note that if we add third, fourth or many firms this will not change the outcome, the prices still will be $c$.
        \item This is not the case for Cournot competition, in which firms manage to obtain some market power as long as the number of firms is not too large. 
        
    \end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Example 1: Homework}
    \textbf{Competitive Equilibrium}
    \par 
 Remember that in competitive equilibrium we have marginal revenue ($MR$) is equal to marginal cost ($MC$). Firm revenue is equal $p\times q$, and cost is equal  $c(q)=c\times q$. In this case we have that 
\[ MR= p, \text{ and } MC=c. 
\]

Therefore, $p^{CE}=c$. 
\par 
 Now suppose,  inverse consumer demand is $p(q)=250-q$, if $q<250$, and $p(q)=0$ if $q\geq 250$ and variable cost is  $c(q)=20\times q$. Find competitive price ($p^{CE}$) and output ($q^{CE}$). \textbf{Hint:} Use consumer demand function $q(p)$.

\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Example 2: Homework}
    \textbf{Monopolistic Competition}
\par
Assume there is a single firm producing an output q, with a variable cost $c(q)=20\times q$. 
      Inverse consumer demand is $p(q)=250-q$, if $q<250$, and $p(q)=0$ if $q\geq 250$.
 Firm is profit maximizing, and it has market power over both price and quantity. 
 \begin{enumerate}
     \item Find consumer demand function $q(p)$. 
     \item Find firm's profit function $\pi(q)$.
     \item Define firm's maximization problem. 
     \item Find the first order conditions. 
     \item Find monopoly price ($p^M$) and output ($q^M$). \textbf{Hint:} Either use consumer demand, or inverse demand. 
     \item Compare monopoly prices and output to competitive ones.
     
 \end{enumerate}

\end{frame}
\begin{frame}{Example 3: Homework}
    \textbf{Cournot Duopoly}
\par 
    Consider Cournot Duopoly example with demand $p(q)=250-q$, if $q<250$, and $p(q)=0$ if $q\geq 250$, and $q=q_1+q_2$. The costs of both firms are $c_1(q_1)=20q_1$, $c_2(q_2)=20q_2$. Firms are competing on quantity.
    \begin{enumerate}
        \item Formally describe the game (players, strategies, payoff functions). 
        \item Find best response correspondence of firm 1 when firm 2 is producing constant output $q_2$. Do the same for firm 2. 
        \item Find iterated elimination of strictly dominated strategies equilibria. 
        \item Find Nash equilibrium outputs for firm 1 ($q_1^{CD}$)  and ($q_2^{CD}$). 
        \item Find total output produced  by both firms and price $p^{CD}$.
        \item Compare  prices and quantities to both competitive and monopoly cases. 
        \item Is there any improvement over monopoly competition? How about competitive outcome? If you are a policy maker, what would you suggest to do to improve the outcome?
        
    \end{enumerate}
    
\end{frame}
\begin{frame}{Example 4: Homework}
\textbf{Bertrand Duopoly}
\par 
Assume that the inverse demand is given by$p(q)=250-q$, if $q<250$, and $p(q)=0$ if $q\geq 250$, and $q=q_1+q_2$. The costs of both firms are $c_1(q_1)=20q_1$, $c_2(q_2)=20q_2$. Consumers buy from the firm whose price is the lowest. In case of a tie, market splits equally between two firms. 
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Find players and strategy spaces in this game. 
    \item What are the quantity functions for both firm 1 and firm 2? 
    \item Find profit function of firm 1 ($\pi_1(p_1,p_2)$) and firm 2 ($\pi_2(p_1,p_2)$).
    \item Find Nash equilibrium in this game. 
    \item How does prices and output differ from competitive outcome? Provide an intuition for your answer. 
    \item As a policy maker, what kind of conclusion you can get from the Examples 1-4?
\end{enumerate}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Summary}
\begin{itemize}
\item Today, we discussed very important topic: firms competing in economy under different setups. 
\item We saw that the desirable outcome is competitive equilibrium outcome, and it leads to highest output produced, and lowest prices for consumers. 
\item When there was imperfect competition, firms obtained market power and affected prices and output. 
\item When competition was on prices, efficiency restored, however, when it was on quantity, the inefficiency remained. 
  \item  Assignment 2 is due next \textbf{Tuesday, September 28th, 2:00 pm}. \textbf{No late submissions.}
\end{itemize}
    
\end{frame}


